Written evidence submitted by the Legal Action Group (LAG) (LAI 0025)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Civil [bold]Legal Aid- the Secret [bold]Legal [bold]Service?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]LAG has found a disturbing reduction in the take-up of legal aid cases in civil law for the first quarte
[normal]r of the current year, 2013/14.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders (LASPO) Act 
[normal]introduced sweeping cuts to scope in legal aid from April this year. What LAG’s research shows is that for the cases which are still covered by legal aid there has been a large reduction in the take-up of legal aid services for these by public. We believe 
[normal]this has been caused by
[normal] a combination of factors
[normal] 
[normal]including, 
[normal]the reduction
[normal] 
[normal]in the number of solicitors firms and charities, such as Citizens Advice Bureaux, offering legal aid
[normal], a perception amongst the
[normal] 
[normal]public 
[normal]that
[normal] 
[normal]they can
[normal] no
[normal]-longer
[normal] 
[normal]get help with any civil law problems 
[normal]and 
[normal]the failure by the government to adequately advertise the availability of services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Downward Trend in Cases[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Previous figures released by LAG show that the number of civil legal aid cases has been in decline over t
[normal]he last few years. It is in the social welfare law (SWL) category that the biggest falls have occurred. From just under half a million cases at their peak in 2009-10 the number of SWL cases had dropped to 293,319 last year.
[normal] The following table breaks down
[normal] the figures for legal help and certificated cases for the five categories of SWL-
