[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The reducing number of SWL cases is surprising given the continuing difficult economic outlook and the numbers of 
[normal]cases reaching the courts and tribunals system. For example in the quarter ending 31
[normal]st
[normal] Dec 2012 there had been a 48% increase in the number of cases brought to the Social Security and Child Support Tribunal.
[normal] Citizens Advice has also reported increasing nu
[normal]mbers of enquiries in the first three quarters of 2012/13. However, in the final quarter Bureaux capacity to deal with specialist cases was reduced as they prepared for the withdrawal of legal aid from much of SWL. 
[normal] We believe the reduction in the numbers
[normal] of cases since 2010 has been caused by changes to the system, such as the reduction in the numbers of cases legal aid firm are permitted to commence, rather than a decrease in the numbers of people needing assistance. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The trend over the last few years 
[normal]ha
[normal]s been of concern, but the
[normal] latest 
[normal]figures 
[normal]for the first quarter of the current year (outlined below) show that the take-up of legal aid services in common areas of 
[normal]civil 
[normal]law has fallen off a cliff.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fewer Cases than Predicted[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The following table shows 
[normal]the percentage number of cases which the government predicted would remain in scope after the cuts were introduced in April-
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Category of law
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Debt
[normal] (mainly housing related)
[normal]26%
[normal]Education
[normal]42%
[normal]Discrimination
[normal]100%
[normal]Housing
[normal]60%
[normal]Welfare Benefits
[normal]0
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The above table refers to legal help cases. Legal help cases 
[normal]involve
[normal] initial advice and assistance to a client. Some cases go onto legal representation, but the bulk of cases referred to in this report remain at the legal help level. For example in 2012/13 there were 81,944 new matters started for legal help 
[normal]with
[normal] debt
[normal] prob
[normal]lems
[normal], but only 353 cases went on to the next level, civil representation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The table below shows the total number of 
[normal]legal help 
[normal]cases for each category of law for the first quarter of the current year, the projected number of cases 
[normal]is 
[normal]based on the governm
[normal]ent’s estimates and the percentage shortfall in the number of cases
[normal] has been calculated by LAG
[normal].
[normal] The analysis is based on figures from the Legal Aid Agency (LAA)
[normal] the new body which was established within the Ministry of Justice from April this year to admi
[normal]nister legal aid. 
