[normal]A total of 3,866 less people than predicted received civil legal aid. 
[normal]This is a total shortfall [bold]of 52%. [bold] The shortfalls do vary between the 
[normal]different 
[normal]categories of law
[normal], with the lowest being 
[normal]in education law 
[normal]at
[normal] 12%
[normal] and the
[normal] highest
[normal] 
[normal]being 
[normal]in discrimination law 
[normal]at
[normal] 77%.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LAG believes that the very large shortfall in discrimination law can be explained by the 100% reduction in the availability of legal aid for employment law cases. 
[normal]In the employment law category 
[normal]the government projected that 78% of cases
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]out of a total of 24,000, 
[normal]would be taken from scope
[normal]. T
[normal]he remaining 22
[normal]% would be discrimination ones. However, m
[normal]ost discrimination law cases usually stem from a dispute in the workplace, but as no legal aid is ava
[normal]ilable for employment law advice people who have been discriminated against are less likely to seek help.
[normal] Another factor in the low take-up of legal aid for discrimination
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]as well as debt 
[normal]cases
[normal],
[normal] might also be the government’s decision to shift all initial
[normal] enquiries onto 
[normal]the Civil Legal Advice (CLA) service which is an internet and telephone based 
[normal]service
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Low take-up of [bold]Housing [bold]and Debt [bold]Cases[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Legal Aid is 
[normal]still 
[normal]available for people in danger of losing their homes
[normal], homelessness cases and for some 
[normal]disrepair matters
[normal]. Such cases can be covered by either the debt or housing law categories. 
[normal]Debt legal aid contracts were mainly concentrated among advice charities such as Citizens Advice Bureaux. These have seen the biggest reduction in the number of lega
[normal]l aid contract holders
[normal].
[normal] According to
[normal] the national charity,
[normal] Citizen’s Advice
[normal],
[normal] there are now only just over 30
[normal] 
[normal]of its 
[normal]bureaux with legal aid contracts, down from a total of over 160 before the cuts were imposed in April.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Birmingham CAB held one of the largest legal aid contracts in the not for profit sector. The service operates out of four offices in 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal]. Prior to April it employed 27 specialist caseworkers in debt and welfare benefits, but according to Emma Cook, 
[normal]acting Chief Executive
[normal] of the Bureaux, all 
[normal]of 
[normal]these post holders 
[normal]have 
[normal]had to be made redundant or redeployed, “the loss of the £750,000 contract for legal aid meant a third of the service 
[normal]went
[normal] from 31
[normal]st
[normal] March. These specialist services cannot be replaced b
[normal]y volunteers.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Russell Conway, is an experienced housing law solicitor who recently won the Legal Aid Lawyer of the Year Award for his work in housing and other areas of social welfare law
[normal]. He blames in part the unrelenting bad news on legal aid for the 
[normal]reduction in cases, “the public are quite good at picking-up on the grim stuff”, but “find it difficult to know exactly what
[normal]’
[normal]s happened.” He 
[normal]s
[normal]ays that “some local authorities and social landlords have been peddling the rumour that legal aid for housing cas
[normal]es has been abolished completely
[normal]. Some of my
[normal] clients have been pleasantly surprised when 
[normal]I’ve
[normal] told them they can still get legal aid for their case.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many practitioners have told LAG they believe that there is a problem 
[normal]over the 
[normal]identification of clients
[normal] who are eligible for legal aid as the rules now are so complex.
[normal] Vicky Ling is a management consultant and author of LAG’
[normal]s Legal Aid Handbook. 
[normal]She
[normal] says that
[normal] “the Legal Aid Agency is now so draconian in their audits that practitioners fear applying for lega
[normal]l aid unless they are absolutely certain it will fall within the rules.” 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Welfare benefits cases were cut by 100% from April, but 135 new cases were commenced in April, May and June this year. This is around 3% of the cases which were reported in the same
[normal] period last year. 
[normal]LAG believes that these cases are Higher Tribunal, Court of Appeal and Supreme Court cases which relate to an appeal on a point of law,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Only in family law does the number of cases exceed the projected number of cases significantly 
[normal](14%), but this could be due to a combination of the tapering effect and the greater number of firms still providing services
[normal], (from April there were 2227 family law legal aid contracts against 
[normal]703 housing and debt contracts
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lack of Marketing[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Pam Kenw
[normal]orthy is the 
[normal]Legal Director
[normal] at the solicitors 
[normal]firm Howells LLP
[normal]. The firm 
[normal]won one of the contracts for the telephone gateway service. 
[normal]Kenworthy
[normal] believes that both lawyers and the public need to get the message that employment law discrimination cases are st
[normal]ill covered by legal aid. “The CLA providers would obviously like the Ministry of Justice to consider raising the profile of the service with stakeholders as it seems daft to have a service that no one knows about.” 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Legal Aid Practitioners Group 
[normal](LAPG) has expressed concerns to the government about the adequacy of the marketing of legal aid services, “we believe it has been inadequate
[normal] and is some cases unfortunately misleading
[normal]” says Carol Storer, LAPG Director, “the information which is available 
[normal]does not provide clear guidance to the public about what is covered by legal aid.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Exceptional Cases[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As part of the provisions in the LASPO Act the government int
[normal]roduced a revamped exceptional funding
[normal] rule to ensure people with cases out of scope c
[normal]an
[normal] get
[normal] assistance if their human rights had been breached
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The LAA had estimated that there would 5-7000 cases granted annually.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]F
[normal]igures 
[normal]from the LAA 
[normal]reveal that there were only 233 applications for exceptional funding in 
[normal]April, May and June this year the first
[normal] quarter of 
[normal]operation 
[normal]for
[normal] the scheme.  Only two grants of exceptional funding 
[normal]to clients 
[normal]have been made in non-inquest cases (funding for inquest cases was usually granted under the previous exceptional funding scheme). The Public Law Project 
[normal](PLP) 
[normal]has 
[normal]expressed concerns about these figures as they are very low compared to the original projections and there is evidence of poor quality decision making in the cases being rejected.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is difficult not to conclude that the LAA is being deliberately obstruc
[normal]tive in not allowing many of the claims
[normal]. The PLP talks of the “poor quality of decision-making” in the cases which it has seen and expresses concern about the low number of applicants who seek reviews of the decisions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LAG has spoken to many practitioner
[normal]s who are not prepared to apply for exceptional funding as they have no guarantee of payment for the work
[normal] unless the application is suc
[normal]c
[normal]essful
[normal]. 
[normal]Chris Johnson of the Community Law Partnership in 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal] has submitted a number of exceptional funding appli
[normal]cations but
[normal] says
[normal] “we cannot afford to keep on doing this work pro-bono.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Civil Legal Aid under threat[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The reduced take-up of civil legal aid has been caused by the combination of factors described above, dwindling numbers of firms and agencies 
[normal]undertaking legal
[normal] aid
[normal], increased bureaucratic hurdl
[normal]es before legal aid is granted 
[normal]and a low profile, caused by lack of marketing and a public perception that legal aid is no-longer available for civil cases. Either by accident or design
[normal],
[normal] the government see
[normal]ms to be presiding over a secret legal service
[normal]. The fear is if nothing is done to increase the take-up of civil legal aid
[normal],
[normal] the remaining services will wither away as the lack of use will be used to justify their loss.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LAG calls on the government to increa
[normal]se the profile of civil legal aid services 
[normal]through better marketing via
[normal] the web and other channels. We are also calling for an urgent review of the exceptional funding mechanism as it is clearly not providing the human rights safety net it was intended to.
[normal]  
